==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|abjeccioun}}, from '''either''' {{der|en|frm|abjection}} '''or''' {{der|en|LL.|abiectiō|abiectiōn-}}, from {{der|en|la|abiectus||cast down}}.<ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976|page=4}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5}}</ref>
* See [[abject]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/æbˈd͡ʒɛk.ʃn̩/}}
{{audio|en|EN-Abjection.ogg|Audio}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A low or [[downcast]] condition; [[meanness]] of spirit; [[abasement]]; [[degradation]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''an '''abjection''' from the beatific regions where God, and his angels and saints, dwell forever''
# {{lb|en|obsolete|chiefly|figuratively}} Something cast off; garbage. {{defdate|Attested from around (1350 to 1470) until the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The act of bringing down or [[humbling]]; casting down. {{defdate|Attested from the early 16<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: "''The '''abjection''' of the king and his realm.''"
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The act of casting off; [[rejection]]. {{defdate|Attested from the early 17<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|biology|mycology}} The act of dispersing or casting off [[spore]]s.

